<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A capped league, is it for you?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.77)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10936'>Brandon "fengrecluse" Erwin</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10936&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 16, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> With the release of the Two Towers expansion for LOTR I will probably be participating in a capped league with it’s release as a way to get familiar with the game and see if it’s something I want to continue playing.  A capped league is an agreement between several different players to cap their spending of the card game to a certain amount of boosters per week.  This is something that I and others did with the initial release of LOTR and was a great way to begin playing the card game.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
What are the benefits of a capped league?  <br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
First and foremost it reduces the amount of money that a person has to invest to play the game at a competitive level.  Aftecloberrson has spent $20 for the initial buy in of a starter deck and a few boosters, it’s only $7 a week for two boosters.  Everyone that I know can scrap together $7 a week.  Since everyone I know can afford $7 a week this allows you to get others to get involved in the game.  Maybe you have a buddy/girlfriend/boyfriend that would be interested in the game if they had gotten into it from the beginning.  Well, here’s a new beginning to get those people involved.  <br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Second, it levels the playing field.  When everyone has access to the same card pool, it instantly creates a level playing field for all of those involved.  Everyone is learning the rules together and this encourages people to play the game, sometimes even more than the low dollar amount.  Sure, there can be a booster pack that has that one good card that may give that player an advantage, but after a few more weeks of drafting that advantage will be overcome and the playing field will be level yet again.  <br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Third, a capped league hones your deck building abilities.  When you have a bunch of cards that are not obviously good by themselves, it forces a player to create a deck that works well with a limited amount of cards.  <br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Fourth, when you have a limited pool of cards, you begin to look at all of those common and uncommon and crappy rares that you would normally glance over.  This gives you a greater familiarity of the cards and how they can be used.  This familiarity allows you to surprise an opponent and also prevents you from being surprised when an opponent plays those cards against you.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Fifth, it allows you test the waters of game.  Since you’re limited to $7 a week, you don’t have to jump into the game right away.  If you like the game then you can spend more money, if you don’t like the game you can quit before you’ve committed yourself to the deep end.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Sixth, beating an opponent in a tournament with your honed league deck has a great sense of satisfaction to it.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Seventh, it’s temporary.  Every capped league is going to end at some time.  You can commit to the league for a time and when everyone feels that the capped league has served its purpose it can ended without any fuss.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
For those that aren’t too sure about this next expansion of LOTR(as I am) or for those who know a bunch of people who would get involved if it weren’t for the expense and learning curve, I encourage you to begin a capped league.  It’s a lot of fun and gets a lot more people involved.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Rules for a capped league, or what we’ve found worked best:<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Entry into the league is one starter deck and 3 boosters.  This is about $20 dollars.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Each week you can draft up 2 boosters or roughly $7.  It’s best to draft as a group because then you can immediately begin trading, putting the new cards in your deck and playing.  Draft day isn’t just about playing the game, it’s about getting together with your friends and socializing by trading cards and discussing what a new card could do for your deck.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
We started our first league by not allowing any trading outside the league.  In hindsight, this was not a good move because other card players saw us as a little bit elitist.  If you want you league to be elitist then by all means limit the trading to those who are only participating in the league.  If you want to be practical, don’t place any restrictions on trading.<br>
<br><br>
<br><br>
Encourage everyone you know to get involved.  Stress the $20 entry fee and the fact that there is a designated day to get together and draft.  The fact that a group of people are getting together once a week is enough for most people to decide they want to get involved.<br>
